Orlando, you are so freaking talented. We are so lucky to watch you share your stories and experiences through your various mediums. We want to start celebrating you! We are launching an #MixTapeOrlando IGTV station that will feature new music from our community, from Grammy award winning producers to youth voices. If you want us to showcase your music, tag us! We are launching with a track from Sean Mingo's new album 'T.K.T.B.' (Read our full interview with him on our website! Link in bio)

We have the exclusive on his new COLD WAR PT. 1 video.
Checkout what he had to say about his vision creating this video:

"The video symbolizes a rebirth from the ashes...a reckoning from wrongdoing and oppression"
...
Words and Music by: @mingosean
Directed and filmed by @halliesettle

node.text:
“No one is free until we are all free.” - Martin Luther King Jr.

Words from @sdotka_music 

"I see that the world is literally at a standstill. We are all effected by stereotypes and hatred. Our history has a tendency of repeating and the time to put an end is now. I thought to myself, how can I play a part in healing the nation and obviously I can’t do this alone. This song brings the perspective of someone’s final moments after having their life taken by law enforcement. People tend to judge the situation outside looking in but I wanted to shed light to those actually in the situation. The goal isn’t to spread anger but to talk to all sides involved from police, to people who are angry and riot, to those who want peace, so we can make a difference with peace, not hatred."

🎥 by @jonisblack and @studioisblack
Produced by @realartie .

node.text:
Words & concept by @zules5 & @juaniitovargas 

———————————

As dancers we got together to create more than just choreography. We created for something much bigger than us. We know that we are living in some very weird & crazy times. Not only are we in a pandemic but we also have people suffering from injustice & racism. With everything that’s been happening to our black community all around our country, I think it was time that we stood with them to make a change. We did not make this video for the sake of getting views nor did we make this video because BLM is a trend. As a matter of fact, we decided to create this to show our support in the best way we know how & that’s through dance. Huge thank you to @kingkingski for making us these mask, to ensure that all of the dancers felt safe. Also thank you to everyone for being a part of this project & helping our vision come to life. I’m so incredibly lucky to know such talented people. Another thank you to the choreographers, Juan, Jazlyn, Niko, Clarissa, Poly & Chad. We wouldn’t have been able to do this without you.🙏🏼

———————————

We hope this sheds some light to all of you & show you that it doesn’t matter where you come from or what the color of your skin is. At the end of the day, we are all HUMANS. That being said, all lives don’t matter unless ALL BLACK LIVES MATTER!✊🏼❤️

node.text: Today is Juneteenth, a joyous holiday celebrating the liberation of those who had been held as slaves in the United States. Although President Abraham Lincoln issued the preliminary Emancipation Proclamation on Sept. 22, 1862, it didn’t go into effect until Jan. 1, 1863. This declaration freed all slaves in the Union, but not the Confederate states. Gen. Robert E. Lee's surrender of the south did not take place until April 9, 1865, and it took Union troops two months to make their way to occupy Texas. On June 19, Gen. Gordon Granger read aloud the contents of "General Order No. 3," announcing the total emancipation of those held as slaves. June 19 – Juneteenth – is a day all Americans should celebrate, and with that in mind we have asked a few music leaders in our community to share a song that has been sung within the Black community since the Segregation Era. “Lift Ev’ry Voice and Sing" – often referred to as the Black national anthem – was written as a poem by James Weldon Johnson in 1900 and set to music by his brother J. Rosamond Johnson in 1905. In 1919, the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) dubbed it "the Negro national hymn" for its power in voicing a cry for liberation and affirmation for African-American people. We are far from repairing the historic oppression of Black communities, but today let’s celebrate Black Joy, Black Excellence and Black Pride! @chevl21 @organizeflorida @operaorlando

node.text: Actions speak louder than words. “It’s so easy to be ignorant and ignore the problems going on in the world when you are in the safety of your home watching things happen on tv. We are living through history and it is our responsibility to help stand up against the injustices happening to the Black community. Turn off the tv and act!” @shaynegraham

The end of the track leaves room for hope and optimism for a brighter day.” @soulbaseband https://bit.ly/2MIMTSN

node.text:
Heads up, there is no sound until he gets out of the car. Read the whole story. #LinkInBio #BodyCamFootage

Here is a synopses from @orangecosheriff. There is video of Sheriff Mina’s statement on Twitter @orangecosheriff 
On June 3, 2020 at about 7:20pm, deputies were monitoring the peaceful demonstration near Curry Ford Road and Chickasaw Trail when they observed a vehicle stopped in a traffic lane with its hazard lights on. A traffic stop was initiated, deputies explained the reason for the traffic stop and asked the driver to step out of the vehicle but she refused numerous times and was told by deputies that they would remove her if she didn’t step out.

A deputy first attempted to reach inside the car through the open driver’s side window to unlock the door, but the driver raised the window on the deputy’s arm/hand. The deputy broke the window with his agency issued baton and the driver was removed from the vehicle and placed in handcuffs. The driver requested medical attention and was transported to the hospital with minor injuries to her face from broken glass. #OrlandoProtest #ThisIsOrlando #BlackLivesMatter #orlando #florida #StaySafe #SocialDistancing #journalism #staysafe #supportlocaljournalism #keeporlandoweeklyfree

“I truly have no words to try to describe, or Every time this happens it just a reminder that my dad , my brother, my nieces & nephew, my cousins, even myself could be next... no matter if we comply or not if someone that’s suppose to protect us feels like killing us they can, and they can get away with it... at least on this side of Earth. It’s not right. I just ask that more than anything pray for my faith, these things always cause a mental, and emotional war.  Through my photography & videography visuals  speak louder where words fails.”
Filmed and created by @meansupreme

node.text:
Orange County Tax Collector Scott Randolph is giving his employees two options: the 💉or the 🚪. With 316 employees processing drivers' licenses, vehicle registration and property taxes, “We’re an agency that just can’t be closed,” says Randolph. Employees who qualify for exemption from the vaccine will be required to get a COVID test weekly and must wear face masks indoors.
